                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d417">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.48B/91: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Woods</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-09-18T16:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 18, 1923—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>173. Your Numbers 63 and 65, of September 17.<note n="29" xml:id="d417fn29"
                        >Neither printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The American Red Cross is entirely satisfied to have you the head of their relief
                    program and to have Brigadier General McCoy acting under you as liaison with the
                    Japanese authorities in the capacity of Director General or otherwise, as you
                    may deem best, it being understood that all purchasing and distribution of
                    supplies are to be made by the Imperial Japanese Bureau, to which the
                    contributions of the American Red Cross are to be turned over.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
